        <headline>Special Weather Statement issued April 4 at 1:29AM EDT by NWS Charleston WV</headline>
        <description>At 129 AM EDT, Doppler radar was tracking strong thunderstorms along
a line extending from 6 miles northeast of Athens to 6 miles
southwest of New Haven. Movement was east at 65 mph.

HAZARD...Wind gusts up to 40 mph and pea size hail.

SOURCE...Radar indicated.

IMPACT...Gusty winds could knock down tree limbs and blow around
unsecured objects. Minor hail damage to vegetation is
possible.

Locations impacted include...
Portland, Sandyville, Lakin, Reedsville, Stroud Run State Park,
Pomeroy, Washington, Little Hocking, Darwin, Cottageville, Coolville,
Tuppers Plains, Syracuse, Amesville, Lubeck, Racine, The Plains,
Mount Alto, Stockport, and Ravenswood.

This includes the following highways...
Interstate 77 in West Virginia between mile markers 140 and 155.
Route 50 in West Virginia between mile markers 1 and 2.
</description>
        <instruction>If outdoors, consider seeking shelter inside a building.

Torrential rainfall is also occurring with these storms and may lead
to localized flooding. Do not drive your vehicle through flooded
roadways.

These storms may intensify, so be certain to monitor local radio
stations and available television stations for additional information
and possible warnings from the National Weather Service.</instruction>
